 18  /-- Format the given tactic state. If `target_lhs_only` is true and the target
 19      is of the form `lhs ~ rhs`, where `~` is a simplification relation,
 20      then only the `lhs` is displayed.
 21  
 22      Remark: the parameter `target_lhs_only` is a temporary hack used to implement
 23      the `conv` monad. It will be removed in the future. -/

290  /--  Helper tactic for creating simple applications where some arguments are inferred using
291      type inference.
292  
293      Example, given
294      ```
295          rel.{l_1 l_2} : Pi (α : Type.{l_1}) (β : α -> Type.{l_2}), (Pi x : α, β x) -> (Pi x : α, β x) -> , Prop
296          nat     : Type
297          real    : Type
298          vec.{l} : Pi (α : Type l) (n : nat), Type.{l1}
299          f g     : Pi (n : nat), vec real n
300      ```
301      then
302      ```
303      mk_app_core semireducible "rel" [f, g]
304      ```
305      returns the application
306      ```
307      rel.{1 2} nat (fun n : nat, vec real n) f g
308      ```
309  
310      The unification constraints due to type inference are solved using the transparency `md`.
311  -/

374  /-- Configuration options for the `apply` tactic.
375  
376  - `new_goals` is the strategy for ordering new goals.
377  - `instances` if `tt`, then `apply` tries to synthesize unresolved `[...]` arguments using type class resolution.
378  - `auto_param` if `tt`, then `apply` tries to synthesize unresolved `(h : p . tac_id)` arguments using tactic `tac_id`.
379  - `opt_param` if `tt`, then `apply` tries to synthesize unresolved `(a : t := v)` arguments by setting them to `v`.
380  - `unify` if `tt`, then `apply` is free to assign existing metavariables in the goal when solving unification constraints.
381     For example, in the goal `|- ?x < succ 0`, the tactic `apply succ_lt_succ` succeeds with the default configuration,
382     but `apply_with succ_lt_succ {unify := ff}` doesn't since it would require Lean to assign `?x` to `succ ?y` where
383     `?y` is a fresh metavariable.
384  -/

490      We say `t` occurs in `e` by keyed matching iff there is a subterm `s`
491      s.t. `t` and `s` have the same head, and `is_def_eq t s md`
492  
493      The main idea is to minimize the number of `is_def_eq` checks
494      performed. -/
495  meta constant kdepends_on (e t : expr) (md := reducible) : tactic bool

523  /-- By default, Lean only considers local instances in the header of declarations.
524      This has two main benefits.
525      1- Results produced by the type class resolution procedure can be easily cached.
526      2- The set of local instances does not have to be recomputed.
527  
528      This approach has the following disadvantages:
529      1- Frozen local instances cannot be reverted.
530      2- Local instances defined inside of a declaration are not considered during type
531         class resolution.
532  
533      This tactic resets the set of local instances. After executing this tactic,
534      the set of local instances will be recomputed and the cache will be frequently
535      reset. Note that, the cache is still used when executing a single tactic that
536      may generate many type class resolution problems (e.g., `simp`). -/
537  meta constant unfreeze_local_instances : tactic unit
id                                            └────┘ └──┘
src                                           └────┘ └──┘
